p.me:
\begin{align*}
                    v_{ave} & = \dfrac{\text{Change in position}}{\text{Length of time
                    interval}} \\
                    & = \dfrac{s(4)-s(1)}{4-1} && \text{Substitute } t = 1 \text{ and }
                    t = 4 \\
                    & = \dfrac{256 - 112}{3} && \text{Substitute values for } s(4) \text
                    { and } s(1) \\
                    & = 48 \text{ } \dfrac{\text{ft}}{\text{s}} && \text{Simplify} \\
                    \end{align*}

ShortAnswer.question:
If s(2) = 106 feet and s(5) = 10  feet, the average velocity
               during that time interval is  \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}}

               \dfrac{\text{feet}}{\text{second}}.

CorrectExplanation.me:
\begin{align*}
                  \text{Average velocity} &= \dfrac{\text{Change in position}}{\text{Length of
                  time interval}} \\
                  &= \dfrac{-96}{3} \\
                  &= -32 \, \dfrac{\text{feet}}{\text{second}} \\
                  \end{align*}

ShortAnswer.question:
The change in position of the ball over the time interval [1,3] is 32
                \text{ ft.} So the ball’s average velocity over that interval is \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}}
                \dfrac{\text{feet}}{\text{second}}.

list.item:
The average velocity measures the change in the object’s position divided by the
                length of the time interval: v_{ave} = \dfrac{\text{ Change in position }}{\text{
                Length of time interval }}\text{.}

choice.explanation:
The term s(b) gives the position at time t = b \text{,}
                   and the term s(a) represents the position at time t = a \text{.}
                   So s(b) - s(a) represents \text{rise}, the change in position.

TextResource.Text:
The function s(t) = -16t^2 + 128t
           represents the height in feet t seconds after a ball is thrown. Find the average
           velocity of the ball from t=1 to t=5 \text{.}

list.item:
The average velocity can be interpreted graphically as the slope of the secant
                line between two points on the graph of s(t): v_{ave} = \dfrac{s(b) -
                s(a)}{b-a} \text{.}

p.me:
\begin{align*}
                    v_{ave} & = \dfrac{s(3) - s(1)}{3 - 1} \\
                    & = \dfrac{240 \text{ ft} - 112 \text{ ft}}{2 \text{ s}} \\
                    & = \dfrac{128 \text{ ft}}{2 \text{ s}} \\
                    & = 64 \dfrac{\text{ft}}{\text{s}} \\
                    \end{align*}

MultipleChoice.question:
The function s(t) represents the height of a ball in feet at t
               seconds. The instantaneous velocity of the ball at t = 2 is \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}}
               \text{.}

choice.explanation:
The ball is thrown at t=0 \text{,} so the velocity the instant
                    the ball is thrown is the slope of the tangent line at t=0 \text{,} not t=2
                    \text{.}

The instantaneous velocity at t=2 is the number that the
                    average velocities on intervals [t,2] and [2,t] approach as t
                    gets closer to 2 \text{.}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
As the length of the intervals shrink and the endpoints get closer
                to 2 \text{,} the average velocities seem to get closer to 32
                \dfrac{\text{feet}}{\text{second}} \text{.}

list.item:
The instantaneous velocity at t=a is the value the average velocities
                approach on the intervals of the form [t,a] and [a,t] as t
                becomes close to a \text{.}

The slopes of the secant lines associated with the average velocities on
                intervals like [a,t] and [t,a] as t gets close to a
                approach the slope of the tangent line at t=a \text{.}

CorrectExplanation.p:
The slope (rate of change) was previously computed to be m = -2 \text{.}
                 The constant b is the y\text{-intercept} and can be found on the
                 table: b = f(0) = 5 \text{.}

